Class is a classification of age, based on the rings. Class has a very broad range for A5, where over 13 different ring values ar included in this class, as compared to only 2-4 ring values for the classes a1=a4. A5, I predict, will hold many of the outliers. The majority of the abalones belong in the A3 class out of all the classes, at 9 and 10 rings.

### Section 6: (11 points) Conclusions from the Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA).

Conclusions

Essay Question 1) (5 points) Based solely on these data, what are plausible statistical reasons that explain the failure of the original study? Consider to what extent physical measurements may be used for age prediction.

Answer: (I believe the lack of direct correlation between volume and weight to age is part of why the study failed. I believe another element was the difficulty in determining sex for young abalone. There is a correlation between weight, shuck and volume for abalones related to their sex, and have a big bucket of infant abalone with not sex classification make it difficult to explore that correlation. Not knowing sex also makes it difficult to predict the breeding potential of the species, because you dont know how many females are able to reproduce. )

Essay Question 2) (3 points) Do not refer to the abalone data or study. If you were presented with an overall histogram and summary statistics from a sample of some population or phenomenon and no other information, what questions might you ask before accepting them as representative of the sampled population or phenomenon?

Answer: (I would ask how does this sample reflect agains the total population? Is the sample as diverse in age, demographic, gender, socioeconomic status, etc as the main population? If the person doesnt know, I would ask for more data to do that analysis myself. I would also ask how long the data was collected for, as the data may be influenced by a catastrophic recent event so any results would be specific to that event and not to the population as a whole. )

Essay Question 3) (3 points) Do not refer to the abalone data or study. What do you see as difficulties analyzing data derived from observational studies? Can causality be determined? What might be learned from such studies?

Answer: (Yes - observational studies are difficult as people are ultimately unreliable. How we interpret and document information is non-standardized so when determining causality, there are many factors that can influence the study and therefore the data. There are also many things we as humans learn to ignore, as our brains can only process so much. One of these elements we ignore could contribute to the causality of something and we wouldnt know because we didnt document it/collect info on it. However, observational studies are helpful for providing context around events and data sets, as well as giving you a direction to start looking when thinking of what to research next, or where data may be missing. In other words, observational studies are helpful with influence and understanding, but they very rarely give the whole picture and we should be cautious when relying on their results alone. )
